{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f2fcfbaa-2fe1-4675-b444-17f955f0fcb5","content":"The template has the required core fields but has a few gaps before it's NuGet-ready:\n\n**✅ Present & correct:** `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags` (language + type), `symbols`\n\n**❌ Missing / should fix:**\n\n1. **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for tooling validation.\n2. **`description`** — Missing entirely. Critical for NuGet discoverability; users see this in `dotnet new search`.\n3. **`groupIdentity`** — Recommended (e.g., `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`) so the template engine can group related templates across versions.\n4. **`preferNameDirectory`** — Should be `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n\n**⚠️ Minor considerations:**\n- No `defaultName` — defaults to the template engine's fallback. Consider setting one (e.g., `\"MyWebApi1\"`).\n- The `Framework` symbol looks correct but isn't wired to a `replaces` — make sure the actual `.csproj` in the template content uses `net9.0` as the literal that gets substituted via `sourceName` or a custom replacement.\n\n**Verdict:** Not quite ready — at minimum add `$schema` and `description` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bdb827db-8052-41dd-865b-2dfd21e910ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json against the .NET template engine schema requirements for NuGet publishing.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and tooling support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates to group multiple related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **`sourceName`** — Present, good.\n6. **`identity`** — Present, good.\n\n\n7. **`shortName`** — Present, good.\n8. **`author`** — Present, good.\n9. **`classifications`** — Present, good.\n10. **`tags`** — Present with language and type, good.\n\nThe real concern for NuGet publishing is less about the template.json itself and more about how it's packaged in the `.nuspec` or `.csproj`. Looking at what's actually required versus what's just recommended, the template only needs `identity` and `name` to be valid — both of which are already there.\n\nThe most impactful missing piece is the `description` field, which matters for NuGet discoverability. Adding a `$schema` reference would help with validation too. I should also mention that while the template.json is important, NuGet publishing really depends on the package configuration having `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` set up correctly. The `net9.0` default is reasonable, though `net8.0` might be worth considering depending on the target audience.","outputTokens":906,"requestId":"A855:B994F:76E150E:824FB23:69F15793"},"id":"b75bfcf8-af11-4107-9cec-d0a8d0aaafb1","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:58:15.395Z","parentId":"da828617-c7a3-47c8-9484-1886b44bb54b"}
